Thinking process (8 tools used)\
This is a compelling reframing of what MiroThinker already does \'97 and it reveals both how close the current architecture is to this vision and where the gap lies.\
\
Current: Discretized batch thinking\
The thinker today runs in 3 coarse pulses. It thinks, stops, waits for the swarm to act, then thinks again with enriched context:\
\
\
\
\
The loop is hard-capped at max_iterations=3. pipeline.py:223-227\
\
The thinker produces one monolithic strategy output per iteration, then goes dark while the swarm works. thinker.py:139-152\
\
The swarm (search executor + maestro) runs sequentially after the thinker, not reactively alongside it. pipeline.py:212-227\
\
Your vision: Continuous thinker with reactive swarm\
What you're describing is fundamentally different \'97 the thinker never stops. It's an unbounded reasoning stream, and the swarm agents are reactive observers that:\
\
Read the thinker's evolving thought stream in real-time\
Detect what it's pondering about (questions, gaps, hypotheses)\
Fetch the relevant information (search, scrape, Flock SQL)\
Inject it back into the thinker's context mid-thought\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
This is the difference between batch processing (think \uc0\u8594  act \u8594  think \u8594  act) and stream processing (think continuously while agents reactively feed you).\
\
Why it's architecturally interesting\
The current system already has all the pieces \'97 they're just wired sequentially:\
\
The blackboard (DuckDB corpus + session state) is already the shared memory. condition_manager.py:435-455\
\
The search executor already fires APIs programmatically with no LLM. search_executor.py:405-432\
\
The maestro already has unrestricted Flock SQL access to organise the corpus. maestro.py:46-64\
\
The gossip swarm already does peer-to-peer synthesis (workers \uc0\u8594  refinement \u8594  queen merge). corpus_store.py:2514-2522\
\
The before_model_callback already injects dynamic content into the LLM's context on every call. before_model.py:107-119\
\
The hard constraint\
Current LLM APIs are request-response. You can't inject new tokens into a generation mid-stream. So "pondering in infinity" has to be approximated. Three realistic approaches:\
\
1. Micro-iterations (most feasible today)\
Instead of 3 fat iterations, run N thin ones. The thinker outputs a few paragraphs of thought, the swarm reacts to just those paragraphs, and the thinker continues with a richer \{research_findings\}. The key change: remove max_iterations=3, replace with a token/cost budget, and make each thinker turn much shorter (a single line of questioning rather than a full strategy document). The swarm becomes more granular and responsive.\
\
This is essentially increasing the temporal resolution of the existing loop \'97 from 3 coarse beats to 30 fine-grained ones.\
\
2. Streaming + interrupt (emerging)\
Some inference APIs support streaming output with the ability to cancel and re-prompt. The thinker streams its reasoning; a watcher process parses the stream for questions/hypotheses; when it detects one, it pauses the thinker, dispatches the swarm, and re-prompts with the original thought + injected findings. This is closer to your vision but requires infrastructure that ADK doesn't natively support.\
\
3. Tool-use as implicit injection\
Give the thinker "tools" that aren't really tools \'97 they're the swarm. When the thinker wonders "what are the pricing tiers for X?", instead of writing that into a strategy document for later execution, it calls ponder("pricing tiers for X") and the swarm synchronously fetches and returns the answer inline. The thinker stays "pure reasoning" in spirit but the tools are transparent conduits to the swarm. This is the easiest to implement in ADK \'97 it's just adding tools to the thinker agent that delegate to the search executor and corpus.\
\
Verdict\
The vision is sound and the current architecture is ~70% of the way there. The blackboard, the swarm, the Flock corpus, the reactive callbacks \'97 all exist. What's missing is the temporal model: the thinker currently thinks in discrete, coarse pulses separated by long swarm phases, rather than thinking continuously with the swarm feeding it reactively.\
\
Approach 1 (micro-iterations) is the pragmatic path \'97 it preserves the existing ADK pipeline structure while dramatically increasing the resolution of the think-act cycle. Approach 3 (tool-use as injection) is the most architecturally clean way to make the thinker "ponder and receive" in a single continuous stream.\
\
