\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
\
The key difference from today:\
\
Current	Proposed\
Thinker reads	format_for_thinker() \'97 raw verbal dump of ALL findings	Swarm-synthesised briefing \'97 compressed, angle-partitioned\
Corpus size limit	~128K tokens (one context window)	Unlimited \'97 swarm workers each handle a subset\
Gossip swarm runs	Once, before final synthesiser	Every iteration, before the thinker\
Thinker awareness	Sees individual findings, scores, contradictions	Sees digested narratives, themes, open questions\
Why this works\
The gossip swarm already handles the hard part. _synthesise_gossip partitions findings by angle, has workers synthesise each angle independently, then refines with peer awareness, then merges via a queen: corpus_store.py:2514-2522\
\
Each worker sees only its angle's findings (fits in one context window). The queen sees only the angle summaries (also fits). The output is a compressed narrative that represents the entire corpus regardless of size. Today this feeds the synthesiser. In your vision, it feeds the thinker. corpus_store.py:2528-2555\
\
The thinker already has zero tools and is explicitly designed to be world-unaware: thinker.py:45-48\
\
It reads \{research_findings\} and outputs strategy text. It doesn't care whether that briefing came from a raw dump or a swarm synthesis \'97 the interface is the same. The thinker's instruction already says "read the corpus briefing and reason about gaps." Nothing changes for the thinker itself. thinker.py:40-52\
\
What needs to change concretely\
The change is surprisingly small. The data flow today:\
\
\
maestro_condition_callback \uc0\u8594  corpus.format_for_thinker() \u8594  state["research_findings"]\
condition_manager.py:409-411\
\
Becomes:\
\
\
maestro_condition_callback \uc0\u8594  corpus.synthesise(query) \u8594  state["research_findings"]\
That's it. Replace the raw format_for_thinker() call with a swarm synthesis call in maestro_condition_callback. The thinker reads the same \{research_findings\} template variable \'97 it just gets a swarm-digested briefing instead of a raw dump.\
\
The synthesise() method already auto-selects single-pass for small corpora (<=80 conditions) and gossip for large ones: corpus_store.py:2467-2476\
\
So for small corpora, there's no overhead. For large corpora, the swarm kicks in and the thinker gets a compressed briefing that represents far more knowledge than could fit in its context window.\
\
The tradeoff\
Running the gossip swarm on every iteration (not just once at the end) adds LLM calls. With 3 iterations and, say, 5 angles, that's roughly 3 \'d7 (5 workers + 5 refinements + 1 queen) = 33 extra Flock calls. But these are cheap (small context, short output) compared to the thinker's own reasoning call. And the payoff is that the thinker can now reason over a corpus of 500+ findings that would otherwise overflow its context window.\
\
The thinker also loses visibility into individual finding IDs and granular scores \'97 it sees narratives instead of atoms. This is actually what you want: the thinker should ponder themes and gaps, not micromanage individual data points. The maestro already handles the granular corpus operations.\
\
One additional consideration\
The thinker's instruction currently tells it to "reference specific finding IDs" (e.g., "Finding [3] mentions a forwarding service but lacks pricing"): thinker.py:89-91\
\
With swarm-digested briefings, individual finding IDs may not be preserved. The thinker's instruction would need to shift from referencing atomic findings to referencing themes/angles/narratives. This aligns with your vision \'97 the thinker ponders at a higher level of abstraction, and the swarm handles the atomic details.\
