The key insight: you don't flush the Flock table into the swarm. The maestro reads the Flock table and decides which agents to spawn. The maestro sees:\
\
"There are 200 new findings about pricing that haven't been reasoned about yet"\
"The pricing agent's last thought is 3 iterations old \'97 it's stale"\
"Spawn a new pricing agent with the latest 200 findings"\
The agent processes those findings (conversational understanding, not just a data dump), produces a row_type='thought' row, and that thought goes back into the Flock table. The thinker reads thought rows, not finding rows. The Flock table is the shared substrate \'97 but findings and thoughts are different row types with different semantics.\
\
Flock SQL stays as utility blocks: scoring a finding's trust_score, detecting contradictions between findings, clustering similar findings \'97 these are mechanical Flock operations. They don't need a reasoning agent.\
\
Thought swarm agents do what Flock can't: forming narrative understanding, identifying non-obvious connections, reasoning about what's missing, integrating contradictory evidence into a coherent picture. These need conversational depth, not SQL.\
\
The separation: Flock processes data. The swarm processes meaning.\
\
4. Mutable agent set as flexible context\
This is the most powerful idea. The swarm IS the context. Each agent is a piece of context with conversational understanding. The swarm's properties:\
\
Property	What it means\
Mutable	Agents can be created, destroyed, updated at any time\
Flexible	The swarm grows/shrinks based on what the research needs\
Arbitrarily large	No single context window limit \'97 add more agents\
Conversational understanding	Each agent has processed its data, not just stored it\
This is fundamentally different from a context window. A context window holds text. An agent holds understanding. When you add 50 findings to a context window, you get 50 more lines of text. When you spawn an agent with 50 findings, you get a reasoned analysis of those findings \'97 gaps identified, contradictions noted, connections drawn.\
\
The mutable swarm also solves the staleness problem. In a static context window, old information sits there forever, consuming tokens. In a mutable swarm, the maestro can:\
\
Retire agents whose understanding is superseded by newer data\
Merge agents whose domains overlap (two pricing agents \uc0\u8594  one consolidated pricing agent)\
Split agents whose domain has grown too large (one "market" agent \uc0\u8594  separate "pricing" + "competition" + "regulation" agents)\
Refresh agents with new data (the pricing agent gets 50 new findings \uc0\u8594  re-process and update)\
The gossip swarm workers are the embryonic form of this \'97 dynamically created agents with curated contexts: corpus_store.py:2528-2555\
\
But they're ephemeral (created for synthesis, then discarded) and single-purpose (synthesis only). The thought swarm agents would be persistent (their understanding lives as row_type='thought' rows in the Flock table) and multi-purpose (they reason, not just synthesise).\
\
The open question you're raising\
The tension is: if the swarm agents write their understanding back to the Flock table as row_type='thought' rows, and the thinker reads those rows... then the Flock table becomes the medium through which the swarm communicates with the thinker. The "periodic flush" question becomes: how often does the maestro read the Flock table, decide the swarm is stale, and spawn new/updated agents?\
\
In a continuous pipeline (no fixed phases), this becomes event-driven:\
\
New findings arrive \uc0\u8594  maestro checks which angles are affected \u8594  spawns/refreshes relevant agents\
Thinker produces strategy \uc0\u8594  maestro reads it \u8594  spawns agents for the angles the thinker is pondering about\
An agent's thought is N iterations old \uc0\u8594  maestro retires it and spawns a fresh one with current data\
The Flock table is never "flushed" wholesale into the swarm. Instead, the maestro continuously manages the swarm \'97 it's the gardener tending the agents, deciding which to plant, prune, or replant based on the corpus state and the thinker's needs.\
\
This is where the "continuous pipeline" and "mutable swarm" ideas converge: the pipeline is continuous because the maestro is always tending the swarm, and the swarm is mutable because the maestro is always adjusting it based on what the thinker needs and what the corpus contains. maestro.py:46-64\
\
The maestro's instruction would evolve from "run these 8 scoring steps" to "manage the thought swarm \'97 read the corpus, read the thinker's strategy, decide which agents need to exist, spawn them, retire stale ones, and keep the thinker fed with fresh understanding." maestro.py:143-167\
