Each run opens the same DuckDB file, finds the existing thought lineage, introduces new data-bearing agents, and the thought swarm integrates them. The synthesiser snapshots the swarm's current understanding into a report. The swarm doesn't care about run boundaries \'97 it just keeps accumulating reasoning.\
\
The reconciliation: two rules, one mechanism\
Rule 1: The thought swarm is sovereign. Thought rows (row_type='thought') are never updated or marked consider_for_use=FALSE by any external process. They are immutable once written. The maestro cannot kill, edit, or suppress thoughts. This is enforced structurally \'97 the maestro's execute_flock_sql could be wrapped to reject UPDATE/DELETE on thought rows, or more elegantly, the maestro's instruction simply tells it thoughts are sacred. maestro.py:143-167\
\
Rule 2: The only way to influence the swarm is to introduce data-bearing agents. When the maestro (or the sensory swarm, or the user's follow-up comment) wants to change the swarm's direction, it creates a data-bearing agent \'97 a Flock LLM call with curated context \'97 whose output becomes a new row_type='thought' row. The swarm sees this as a peer's contribution, not an external command.\
\
The mechanism: the fixed-run pipeline is the episode boundary.\
\
\
Episode (run):  \
  1. Open existing DuckDB (or create fresh)  \
  2. Thinker reads prior thought lineage + new findings  \
  3. Search executor fires APIs \uc0\u8594  raw findings enter corpus  \
  4. Maestro scores/organises findings via Flock SQL  \
  5. Maestro introduces data-bearing agents \uc0\u8594  new thought rows  \
  6. Repeat for N iterations (bounded)  \
  7. Synthesiser snapshots current understanding \uc0\u8594  user report  \
  8. Close DuckDB connection (file persists on disk)\
The user asks for more \uc0\u8594  new episode opens the same DuckDB \u8594  the thought swarm already has all prior reasoning \u8594  new data-bearing agents are introduced \u8594  the swarm integrates \u8594  new snapshot report.\
