Why this works\
The fixed-run architecture gives you:\
\
Predictable UX: ask \uc0\u8594  wait \u8594  get report \u8594  comment \u8594  get expanded report\
Bounded cost: each run has max_iterations and a cost budget\
Clean deliverables: the synthesiser produces a polished report at each boundary\
The thought swarm gives you:\
\
Unlimited reasoning depth: across runs, the thought lineage grows without bound\
Academic detachment: the maestro can't corrupt reasoning, only introduce evidence\
Immutable lineage: every thought is preserved, traceable, queryable via SQL\
Arbitrarily large context: the swarm collectively holds more than any single context window\
The DuckDB file is the bridge. It's the thought swarm's persistent memory. Each run is an episode of tending to it. The execution_timeout_seconds=86400 already allows runs up to 24 hours: server.py:371-375\
\
And the stall detector already allows indefinite execution as long as progress is being made: main.py:26-31\
\
So a single run can already be as long as needed. The "fixed" nature is in the iteration count and the fact that it produces a report at the end \'97 not in a hard time limit. The user can always ask for more, and the next run picks up where the thought swarm left off.\
\
The continuous architecture you described is the limit case: max_iterations=\uc0\u8734 , no synthesiser boundary, the swarm runs forever. The fixed-run architecture is the practical case: max_iterations=3, synthesiser at the end, user reviews and optionally continues. Both use the same thought swarm, the same DuckDB, the same immutable lineage. The only difference is where you put the episode boundaries.\
