Thinking process (4 tools used)\
Honestly, I struggle to find strong reasons NOT to share those three principles across modes. Let me try anyway, then explain why the arguments are weak.\
\
Reasons not to share (devil's advocate)\
Immutable lineage\
Fixed-run argument against: A 3-iteration run produces maybe 3-9 thought rows. The overhead of persisting every thought with parent-child lineage, maintaining the append-only invariant, and never allowing cleanup is disproportionate to the value. You could just keep thoughts in memory and discard them when the run ends.\
\
Why this is weak: The DuckDB file already persists across runs \'97 that's how session continuation works. The lineage is what makes continuation meaningful. Without it, a follow-up "expand on the pricing section" has no memory of how the pricing analysis was reached. Even in a short run, the lineage is the audit trail. The cost is one INSERT per thought \'97 negligible. condition_manager.py:608-613\
\
Arbitrarily large context\
Fixed-run argument against: A 3-iteration run with max_iterations=3 typically accumulates 50-200 findings. That fits comfortably in a single context window (~128K tokens). The swarm-as-context mechanism (chunking the corpus, processing in parallel, folding results) adds latency and cost for no benefit when the corpus is small.\
\
Why this is weak: The mechanism should be adaptive, not absent. Below a threshold (like the existing GOSSIP_THRESHOLD = 80), the thinker reads the corpus directly. Above it, the swarm kicks in. The architecture supports both \'97 you don't remove the capability just because most runs don't need it. corpus_store.py:67-68\
\
Academic detachment\
Fixed-run argument against: In a bounded run, the user expects a result within minutes. If the thought swarm goes down a wrong path, academic detachment means you can't course-correct \'97 you can only introduce counter-evidence and hope the swarm integrates it. In a fixed run with 3 iterations, there's no time for the slow process of "convincing" the swarm. Sometimes you need to just override.\
\
Why this is weak: The thinker already has EVIDENCE_SUFFICIENT as an escape hatch. And the maestro's data-bearing agents are fast \'97 a single Flock llm_complete call with curated counter-evidence takes seconds. The "convincing" doesn't need to be slow. thinker.py:139-152\
\
The honest answer\
These three principles are structural invariants of the thought system, not mode-specific features. They should be shared. The mode (fixed vs continuous) determines the time horizon and termination condition, not the nature of thought. A fixed run is just a continuous run with a hard stop.\
\
The only legitimate variation is adaptive thresholds: small corpora skip the swarm overhead, short runs use simpler lineage queries. But the principles themselves \'97 immutability, unbounded capacity, sovereignty \'97 are universal.\
\
The maestro as mixture-of-experts\
This is a sharp observation. The maestro's profile is the inverse of the thought swarm's:\
\
Thought swarm	Maestro\
Context needs	Massive (entire corpus)	Small (corpus summary + strategy)\
Reasoning needs	Broad, integrative	Deep, precise, decisive\
Error tolerance	High (wrong thoughts get diluted by better ones)	Low (a bad scoring pass corrupts the corpus)\
Model priority	Throughput, cost-efficiency	Raw reasoning power\
The current code uses build_model() (the default ADK_MODEL) for the maestro: maestro.py:169-186\
\
While the thinker gets its own model via build_model(thinker=True): thinker.py:139-152\
