The model_config.py already supports per-role model routing with separate API keys and bases: model_config.py:96-124\
\
Extending this to a maestro-specific model is straightforward \'97 add ADK_MAESTRO_MODEL, MAESTRO_API_KEY, MAESTRO_API_BASE env vars and a maestro=True flag to build_model(). But the MoE idea goes further than just "give the maestro a better model." It suggests:\
\
Different models for different maestro operations:\
\
Contradiction detection \uc0\u8594  a model strong at logical reasoning (o3, Claude Opus)\
Redundancy compression \uc0\u8594  a model strong at summarization (Gemini, GPT-4o)\
Scoring/evaluation \uc0\u8594  a model strong at calibrated judgment\
Agent spawning (crafting curated contexts) \uc0\u8594  a model strong at instruction-following\
The Flock proxy already routes through LiteLLM, which supports any provider: flock_proxy.py:1-37\
\
But currently there's only one corpus_model registered with Flock. The MoE approach would register multiple models \'97 scoring_model, reasoning_model, synthesis_model \'97 and the maestro would choose which to use for each execute_flock_sql() call:\
\
\
-- Contradiction detection: use the reasoning specialist  \
SELECT llm_complete(\{'model_name': 'reasoning_model'\}, ...) ...  \
  \
-- Summarization: use the synthesis specialist    \
SELECT llm_complete(\{'model_name': 'synthesis_model'\}, ...) ...\
The maestro itself (the agent making decisions about WHAT to do) would use the most powerful reasoning model available. The Flock operations it dispatches would use specialized models. This is a true mixture-of-experts at the architectural level.\
