\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Memory manipulation extends basic interception to structured context state management. Rather than treating each inference independently, advanced implementations maintain working memory structures that accumulate relevant information across conversation turns, with explicit update, retrieval, and eviction policies . The Semantic Manifold framework formalizes this through "belief injection": introducing targeted linguistic belief fragments into an agent's semantic state ensemble via controlled assimilation operators, providing architectural epistemic control .\cb1 \
\cb3 However, memory manipulation introduces security considerations. Research on plan injection attacks demonstrates that corrupted agent memory and task structure can enable adversary manipulation of high-level actions even under robust prompt defenses . Automata-theoretic models characterize dynamic context injection as adversary-induced state transitions via tainted input, with context-sensitive attack vectors across numerous execution environments . Production implementations require defense-in-depth: input validation, content isolation, output constraints, and behavioral monitoring.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 1.2.3 Latent vector grafting and cross-attention links\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Latent vector grafting represents an advanced research direction that operates below the token level, directly manipulating hidden state representations rather than input sequences. This approach constructs or modifies latent representations of external information that are compatible with the model's internal processing space, potentially achieving more efficient integration than textual encoding .\cb1 \
\cb3 The technical challenge involves representation compatibility: ensuring that grafted vectors maintain semantic coherence with the model's native activations. Techniques include auxiliary encoding networks that map external information to model-compatible spaces, direct activation modification at specific layers, and learned transformation functions optimized for integration quality . Cross-attention links create explicit attention pathways between injected representations and task processing, enabling fine-grained control over contextual influence.\cb1 \
\cb3 For MiroThinker, latent vector techniques remain research-frontier rather than production-standard. Current evidence suggests that well-constructed token-level injection achieves substantial benefits with minimal complexity, making it the preferred approach for most deployments . However, as context length requirements grow and injectable information volumes increase, latent-level techniques may become increasingly relevant. The modular design of dynamic injection enables incremental adoption: systems can begin with token-level injection and incorporate advanced mechanisms as requirements evolve.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 1.2.4 Prompt-level injection via system or user messages\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Prompt-level injection is the most widely deployed and practically accessible implementation mechanism, requiring no model modifications and operating through standard API interfaces . This approach constructs prompts that interleave static instructions with dynamically computed context, presenting the complete package for standard inference processing.\cb1 \
\cb3 System message injection positions dynamic context as persistent operational framework, influencing all subsequent reasoning. This placement is optimal for information with session-wide relevance: current time, user identity, active project context, operational constraints . The system message's typical position at the sequence start ensures strong attention weighting and consistent behavioral influence. Implementation involves template-based construction where static instructions combine with live data variables immediately before API calls.\cb1 \
\cb3 User message injection provides task-specific, turn-level contextualization. This approach analyzes incoming queries to identify contextual needs, retrieves relevant information, and reformulates messages to incorporate this context explicitly . The at-mention pattern (\cb10 @/path/to/file\cb3 ) exemplifies this: user references trigger automatic content retrieval and injection, with the processed message including both original intent and expanded context . User-level injection enables granular relevance matching but may provide less consistent influence than system-level positioning.\cb1 \
\cb3 Hybrid positioning combines both strategies: system messages establish persistent framework, user messages incorporate task-specific details, and explicit delimiters maintain structural clarity. This layered approach balances persistent influence with flexible relevance, supporting diverse interaction patterns without overloading any single injection point.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 1.3 Concrete Examples from Research\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 1.3.1 Temporal data injection: Current date/time in system prompt\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The temporal data injection case provides the most rigorously quantified demonstration of dynamic context injection's performance impact . This implementation addresses a universal requirement\'97enabling agents to reason about current time\'97while exposing the inefficiency of tool-based alternatives.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

