\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The zero-shot personalization capability transforms deployment economics: single model instance serves diverse users with tailored experiences, eliminating variant proliferation and associated operational complexity.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 5.3 Optimal Use Cases\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 5.3.1 Time-sensitive research and information synthesis\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Characteristics: Information currency determines value; rapid change outpaces update cycles; stale information actively misleads .\cb1 \
\cb3 Examples: Financial market analysis, news monitoring, scientific literature tracking, policy development, competitive intelligence.\cb1 \
\cb3 Implementation pattern: Continuous or triggered refresh of key indicators; proactive injection of current baselines; user-initiated injection of specific sources for deep analysis.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 5.3.2 Multi-document analysis with dynamic source selection\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Characteristics: Relevant sources vary by query; comprehensive pre-loading infeasible; user judgment guides relevance; source provenance matters .\cb1 \
\cb3 Examples: Legal document review, academic literature synthesis, code base analysis, due diligence investigation, historical research.\cb1 \
\cb3 Implementation pattern: At-mention or search-initiated injection; intelligent summarization for large sources; hierarchical organization enabling progressive focus; explicit source tracking for verification.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 5.3.3 User-specific personalization without profile retraining\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Characteristics: Diverse user base with distinct needs; privacy constraints on persistent user data; need for immediate adaptation; operational efficiency requires shared infrastructure .\cb1 \
\cb3 Examples: Enterprise research assistants, customer service agents, educational tutoring systems, healthcare decision support, creative collaboration tools.\cb1 \
\cb3 Implementation pattern: Per-session profile injection from authenticated identity; organizational context from directory integration; preference learning with explicit consent; clear user control over personalization scope.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 5.3.4 Rapidly evolving domains requiring current data\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Characteristics: Information half-life measured in days or hours; competitive pressure for currency; error cost of outdated information high; traditional update cycles inadequate .\cb1 \
\cb3 Examples: Cybersecurity threat intelligence, software vulnerability tracking, supply chain monitoring, regulatory compliance, public health surveillance.\cb1 \
\cb3 Implementation pattern: Automated data pipelines with freshness guarantees; threshold-based alerting for significant changes; integration with authoritative sources; explicit currency indicators in agent responses.\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 5.4 Limitations and Risks\cb1 \
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
